# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-global-accelerator
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] The first documented use of anycast routing for topological load-balancing of Internet-connected services was in 1989; the technique was first formally documented in the IETF four years later.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] It was first applied to critical infrastructure in 2001 with the anycasting of the I-root nameserver.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Early objections to the deployment of anycast routing centered on the perceived conflict between long-lived TCP connections and the volatility of the Internet's routed topology.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] In practice, such problems were not observed, and these objections dissipated by the early 2000s.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Many initial anycast deployments consisted of DNS servers, using principally UDP transport.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Measurements of long-term anycast flows revealed very few failures due to mid-connection instance switches, far fewer (less than 0.017% or "less than one flow per ten thousand per hour of duration" according to various sources) than were attributed to other causes of failure.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Numerous mechanisms were developed to efficiently share state between anycast instances.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] And some TCP-based protocols, notably HTTP, incorporated "redirect" mechanisms, whereby anycast service addresses could be used to locate the nearest instance of a service, whereupon a user would be redirected to that specific instance prior to the initiation of any long-lived stateful transaction.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Anycast is implemented in the Internet via Border Gateway Protocol (BGP), where multiple hosts (usually in different geographic areas) are given the same anycast IP address and they all announce it to their BGP table.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Routers consider these to be alternative routes to the same destination, even though they are actually routes to different destinations with the same address.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Routers will often select the path with fewer hops, which leads to the one closer to the client as being selected (often faster).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] It doesn't always happen, as some routers will choose other metrics (least congested, cheapest).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Anycast is supported explicitly in the IPv6 addressing architecture.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] The lowest address within an IPv6 subnet (interface identifier 0) is reserved as the "Subnet Router" anycast address.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] In addition, the highest 128 interface identifiers within a subnet are also reserved as anycast addresses.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] The method used in IPv4 of advertising multiple routes in BGP to multiply-assigned unicast addresses also still works in IPv6, and can be used to route packets to the nearest of several geographically dispersed hosts with the same address.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] This approach, which does not depend on anycast-aware routers, has the same use cases together with the same problems and limitations as in IPv4.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] With the growth of the Internet, network services increasingly have high-availability requirements.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] As a result, operation of anycast services has grown in popularity among network operators.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] All Internet root nameservers are implemented as clusters of hosts using anycast addressing.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] All 13 root servers A–M exist in multiple locations, with 11 on multiple continents.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] (Root servers B and H exist in two U.S. locations.) The servers use anycast address announcements to provide a decentralized service.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] This has accelerated the deployment of physical (rather than logical) root servers outside the United States.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Many commercial DNS providers have switched to an IP anycast environment to increase query performance and redundancy, and to implement load balancing.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] In IPv4 to IPv6 transitioning, anycast addressing may be deployed to provide IPv6 compatibility to IPv4 hosts.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] This method, 6to4, uses a default gateway with the IP address *192.88.99.1*.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] This allows multiple providers to implement 6to4 gateways without hosts having to know each individual provider's gateway addresses.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] 6to4 has been deprecated in response to native IPv6 becoming more prevalent.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Content delivery networks may use anycast for actual HTTP connections to their distribution centers, or for DNS.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Because most HTTP connections to such networks request static content such as images and style sheets, they are generally short-lived and stateless across subsequent TCP sessions.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] The general stability of routes and statelessness of connections makes anycast suitable for this application, even though it uses TCP.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Anycast rendezvous point can be used in Multicast Source Discovery Protocol (MSDP) and its advantageous application as Anycast RP is an intra-domain feature that provides redundancy and load-sharing capabilities.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] If the multiple anycast rendezvous point is used, IP routing automatically will select the topologically closest rendezvous point for each source and receiver.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] It would provide a multicast network with the fault tolerance requirements.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Anycast allows any operator whose routing information is accepted by an intermediate router to hijack any packets intended for the anycast address.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] While this at first sight appears insecure, it is no different from the routing of ordinary IP packets, and no more or less secure.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] As with conventional IP routing, careful filtering of who is and is not allowed to propagate route announcements is crucial to prevent man-in-the-middle or blackhole attacks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] The former can also be prevented by encrypting and authenticating messages, such as using Transport Layer Security, while the latter can be frustrated by onion routing.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Anycast is normally highly reliable, as it can provide automatic failover without adding complexity or new potential points of failure.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Anycast applications typically feature external "heartbeat" monitoring of the server's function, and withdraw the route announcement if the server fails.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] In some cases this is done by the actual servers announcing the anycast prefix to the router over OSPF or another IGP.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] If the servers die, the router will automatically withdraw the announcement.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] "Heartbeat" functionality is important because, if the announcement continues for a failed server, the server will act as a "black hole" for nearby clients; this is the most serious mode of failure for an anycast system.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Even in this event, this kind of failure will only cause a total failure for clients that are closer to this server than any other, and will not cause a global failure.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] However, even the automation necessary to implement "heartbeat" routing withdrawal can itself add a potential point of failure, as seen in the 2021 Facebook outage.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] In denial-of-service attacks, a rogue network host may advertise itself as an anycast server for a vital network service, to provide false information or simply block service.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Anycast methodologies on the Internet may be exploited to distribute DDoS attacks and reduce their effectiveness: As traffic is routed to the closest node, a process over which the attacker has no control, the DDoS traffic flow will be distributed amongst the closest nodes.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] This may be a reason to deploy anycast addressing.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] The effectiveness of this technique depends upon maintaining the secrecy of any unicast addresses associated with anycast service nodes, however, since an attacker in possession of the unicast addresses of individual nodes can attack them from any location, bypassing anycast addressing methods.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Some anycast deployments on the Internet distinguish between local and global nodes to benefit the local community, by addressing local nodes preferentially.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Local nodes are often announced with the no-export BGP community to prevent hosts from announcing them to their peers, i.e. the announcement is kept in the local area.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/anycast] Where both local and global nodes are deployed, the announcements from global nodes are often AS prepended (i.e. the AS is added a few more times) to make the path longer so that a local node announcement is preferred over a global node announcement.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] A **backbone network** or **core network** is a part of a computer network which interconnects networks, providing a path for the exchange of information between different LANs or subnetworks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] A backbone can tie together diverse networks in the same building, in different buildings in a campus environment, or over wide areas.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Normally, the backbone's capacity is greater than the networks connected to it.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] A large corporation that has many locations may have a backbone network that ties all of the locations together, for example, if a server cluster needs to be accessed by different departments of a company that are located at different geographical locations.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] The pieces of the network connections (for example: Ethernet, wireless) that bring these departments together is often mentioned as network backbone.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Network congestion is often taken into consideration while designing backbones.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] One example of a backbone network is the Internet backbone.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] The theory, design principles, and first instantiation of the backbone network came from the telephone core network when traffic was purely voice.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] The *core network* was the central part of a telecommunications network that provided various services to customers who were connected by the access network.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] One of the main functions was to route telephone calls across the PSTN.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Typically the term referred to the high capacity communication facilities that connect primary nodes.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] A core network provided paths for the exchange of information between different sub-networks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] In the United States, local exchange core networks were linked by several competing interexchange networks; in the rest of the world, the core network has been extended to national boundaries.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Core networks usually had a mesh topology that provided any-to-any connections among devices on the network.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Many main service providers would have their own core/backbone networks that are interconnected.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Some large enterprises have their own core/backbone network, which are typically connected to the public networks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Backbone networks create links that allow long-distance transmission, usually 10 to 100 miles, and in certain cases - up to 150 miles.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] This makes backbone network essential to providing long-haul wireless solutions to provide internet service, especially to remote areas.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Authentication: The function to decide whether the user requesting a service from the telecom network is authorized to do so within this network or not.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Call control and switching: call control or switching functionality decides the future course of call based on the call signaling processing.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] E.g. switching functionality may decide based on the "called number" that the call be routed towards a subscriber within this operator's network or with number portability more prevalent to another operator's network.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Charging: This functionality of the collation and processing of charging data generated by various network nodes.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Two common types of charging mechanisms found in present-day networks are prepaid charging and postpaid charging.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Service invocation: The core network performs the task of service invocation for its subscribers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Service invocation may happen based on some explicit action (e.g. call transfer) by user or implicitly (call waiting).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] It's important to note however that service execution may or may not be a core network functionality as third-party networks and nodes may take part in actual service execution.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Gateways: Gateways shall be present in the core network to access other networks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Gateway functionality is dependent on the type of network it interfaces with.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Physically, one or more of these logical functionalities may simultaneously exist in a given core network node.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] A distributed backbone is a backbone network that consists of a number of connectivity devices connected to a series of central connectivity devices, such as hubs, switches, or routers, in a hierarchy.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] This kind of topology allows for simple expansion and limited capital outlay for growth, because more layers of devices can be added to existing layers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] In a distributed backbone network, all of the devices that access the backbone share the transmission media, as every device connected to this network is sent all transmissions placed on that network.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Distributed backbones, in all practicality, are in use by all large-scale networks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Applications in enterprise-wide scenarios confined to a single building are also practical, as certain connectivity devices can be assigned to certain floors or departments.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Each floor or department possesses a LAN and a wiring closet with that workgroup's main hub or router connected to a bus-style network using backbone cabling.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Another advantage of using a distributed backbone is the ability for network administrator to segregate workgroups for ease of management.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] There is the possibility of single points of failure, referring to connectivity devices high in the series hierarchy.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] The distributed backbone must be designed to separate network traffic circulating on each individual LAN from the backbone network traffic by using access devices such as routers and bridges.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] A conventional backbone network spans distance to provide interconnectivity across multiple locations.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] In most cases, the backbones are the links while the switching or routing functions are done by the equipment at each location.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] A collapsed backbone (also known as inverted backbone or backbone-in-a-box) is a type of backbone network architecture.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] In the case of a collapsed backbone, each location features a link back to a central location to be connected to the collapsed backbone.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] The collapsed backbone can be a cluster or a single switch or router.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] The topology and architecture of a collapsed backbone is a star or a rooted tree.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] 2. since the backbone is essentially the back plane or internal switching matrix of the box, proprietary, high performance technology can be used.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] However, the drawback of the collapsed backbone is that if the box housing the backbone is down or there are reachability problem to the central location, the entire network will crash.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] These problems can be minimized by having redundant backbone boxes as well as having secondary/backup backbone locations.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] There are a few different types of backbones that are used for an enterprise-wide network.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] When organizations are looking for a very strong and trustworthy backbone they should choose a parallel backbone.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] This backbone is a variation of a collapsed backbone in that it uses a central node (connection point).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Although, with a parallel backbone, it allows for duplicate connections when there is more than one router or switch.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Each switch and router are connected by two cables.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] By having more than one cable connecting each device, it ensures network connectivity to any area of the enterprise-wide network.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Parallel backbones are more expensive than other backbone networks because they require more cabling than the other network topologies.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Although this can be a major factor when deciding which enterprise-wide topology to use, the expense of it makes up for the efficiency it creates by adding increased performance and fault tolerance.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Most organizations use parallel backbones when there are critical devices on the network.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] For example, if there is important data, such as payroll, that should be accessed at all times by multiple departments, then your organization should choose to implement a parallel backbone to make sure that the connectivity is never lost.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] A serial backbone is the simplest kind of backbone network.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Serial backbones consist of two or more internet working devices connected to each other by a single cable in a daisy-chain fashion.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] A daisy chain is a group of connectivity devices linked together in a serial fashion.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Hubs are often connected in this way to extend a network.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] However, hubs are not the only device that can be connected in a serial backbone.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] Gateways, routers, switches and bridges more commonly form part of the backbone.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/backbone-network] The serial backbone topology could be used for enterprise-wide networks, though it is rarely implemented for that purpose.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] A **content delivery network** (**CDN**) or **content distribution network** is a geographically distributed network of proxy servers and corresponding data centers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] CDNs provide high availability and performance ("speed") through geographical distribution relative to end users, and arose in the late 1990s to alleviate the performance bottlenecks of the Internet as it was becoming a critical medium.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Since then, CDNs have grown to serve a large portion of Internet content, including text, graphics and scripts, downloadable objects (media files, software, and documents), applications (e-commerce, portals), live streaming media, on-demand streaming media, and social media services.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] CDNs are a layer in the internet ecosystem.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Content owners such as media companies and e-commerce vendors pay CDN operators to deliver their content to their end users.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] In turn, a CDN pays Internet service providers (ISPs), carriers, and network operators for hosting its servers in their data centers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] CDN vendors may cross over into other industries like security, DDoS protection and web application firewalls (WAF), and WAN optimization.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Content delivery service providers include Akamai Technologies, Cloudflare, Amazon CloudFront, Qwilt (Cisco), Fastly, CDN77, BunnyCDN, EdgeNext, and Google Cloud CDN.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] CDN nodes are usually deployed in multiple locations, often over multiple Internet backbones.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Benefits include reducing bandwidth costs, improving page load times, and increasing the global availability of content.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] The number of nodes and servers making up a CDN varies, depending on the architecture, some reaching thousands of nodes with tens of thousands of servers on many remote points of presence (PoPs).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Others build a global network and have a small number of geographical PoPs.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Requests for content are typically algorithmically directed to nodes that are optimal in some way.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for performance, locations that are best for serving content to the user may be chosen.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] This may be measured by choosing locations that are the fewest hops or the shortest time to the requesting client, or the highest server performance, to optimize delivery across local networks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for cost, locations that are the least expensive may be chosen instead.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] In an optimal scenario, these two goals tend to align, as **edge servers** that are close to the end user at the edge of the network may have an advantage in performance and cost.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Most CDN providers will provide their services over a varying, defined, set of PoPs, depending on the coverage desired, such as United States, Asia-Pacific, International or Global, etc.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] These sets of PoPs can be called "edges", "edge nodes", "edge servers", or "edge networks" as they would be the closest edge of CDN assets to the end user.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] CDN providers profit either from direct fees paid by content providers using their network, or profit from the user analytics and tracking data collected as their scripts are being loaded onto customers' websites inside their browser origin.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] As such these services are being pointed out as potential privacy intrusions for the purpose of behavioral targeting and solutions are being created to restore single-origin serving and caching of resources.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] In particular, a website using a CDN may violate the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] For example, in 2021 a German court forbade the use of a CDN on a university website, because this caused the transmission of the user's IP address to the CDN, which violated the GDPR.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] CDNs serving JavaScript have also been targeted as a way to inject malicious content into pages using them.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Subresource Integrity mechanism was created in response to ensure that the page loads a script whose content is known and constrained to a hash referenced by the website author.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] The Internet was designed according to the end-to-end principle.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] This principle keeps the core network relatively simple and moves the intelligence as much as possible to the network end-points: the hosts and clients.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] As a result, the core network is specialized, optimized, and simplified to only forward data packets.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Content Delivery Networks extend the transport network by distributing on it a variety of intelligent applications employing techniques designed to optimize content delivery.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] The resulting tightly integrated overlay uses web caching, server-load balancing, request routing, and content services.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Web caches store popular content on servers that have the greatest demand for the content requested.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] These shared network appliances reduce bandwidth requirements, reduce server load, and improve the client response times for content stored in the cache.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Web caches are populated based on requests from users (pull caching) or based on preloaded content disseminated from content servers (push caching).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Server-load balancing uses one or more techniques including service-based (global load balancing) or hardware-based (i.e. layer 4–7 switches, also known as a web switch, content switch, or multilayer switch) to share traffic among a number of servers or web caches.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Here the switch is assigned a single virtual IP address.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Traffic arriving at the switch is then directed to one of the real web servers attached to the switch.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] This has the advantage of balancing load, increasing total capacity, improving scalability, and providing increased reliability by redistributing the load of a failed web server and providing server health checks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] A content cluster or service node can be formed using a layer 4–7 switch to balance load across a number of servers or a number of web caches within the network.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Request routing directs client requests to the content source best able to serve the request.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] This may involve directing a client request to the service node that is closest to the client, or to the one with the most capacity.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] A variety of algorithms are used to route the request.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] These include Global Server Load Balancing, DNS-based request routing, Dynamic metafile generation, HTML rewriting, and anycasting.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Proximity—choosing the closest service node—is estimated using a variety of techniques including reactive probing, proactive probing, and connection monitoring.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] CDNs use a variety of methods of content delivery including, but not limited to, manual asset copying, active web caches, and global hardware load balancers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Several protocol suites are designed to provide access to a wide variety of content services distributed throughout a content network.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] The Internet Content Adaptation Protocol (ICAP) was developed in the late 1990s to provide an open standard for connecting application servers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] A more recently defined and robust solution is provided by the Open Pluggable Edge Services (OPES) protocol.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] This architecture defines OPES service applications that can reside on the OPES processor itself or be executed remotely on a Callout Server.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Edge Side Includes or ESI is a small markup language for edge-level dynamic web content assembly.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] It is fairly common for websites to have generated content.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] It could be because of changing content like catalogs or forums, or because of the personalization.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] This creates a problem for caching systems.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] To overcome this problem, a group of companies created ESI.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] In *peer-to-peer (P2P)* content-delivery networks, clients provide resources as well as use them.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] This means that, unlike client–server systems, the content-centric networks can actually perform better as more users begin to access the content (especially with protocols such as Bittorrent that require users to share).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] This property is one of the major advantages of using P2P networks because it makes the setup and running costs very small for the original content distributor.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] To incentive peers to participate in the P2P network, web3 and blockchain technologies can be used: participating nodes receive crypto tokens in exchange of their involvement.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] If content owners are not satisfied with the options or costs of a commercial CDN service, they can create their own CDN.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] A private CDN consists of PoPs (points of presence) that are only serving content for their owner.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] These PoPs can be caching servers, reverse proxies or application delivery controllers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] It can be as simple as two caching servers, or large enough to serve petabytes of content.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] When a private CDN is deployed within a company network, it is also referred as Entreprise CDN or **eCDN**.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Large content distribution networks may even build and set up their own private network to distribute copies of content across cache locations.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Such private networks are usually used in conjunction with public networks as a backup option in case the capacity of the private network is not enough or there is a failure which leads to capacity reduction.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Since the same content has to be distributed across many locations, a variety of multicasting techniques may be used to reduce bandwidth consumption.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Over private networks, it has also been proposed to select multicast trees according to network load conditions to more efficiently utilize available network capacity.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] The rapid growth of streaming video traffic required large capital expenditures by broadband providers in order to meet this demand and retain subscribers by delivering a sufficiently good quality of experience.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] To address this, telecommunications service providers have begun to launch their own content delivery networks as a means to lessen the demands on the network backbone and reduce infrastructure investments.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Because they own the networks over which video content is transmitted, telco CDNs have advantages over traditional CDNs.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] They own the last mile and can deliver content closer to the end-user because it can be cached deep in their networks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] This deep caching minimizes the distance that video data travels over the general Internet and delivers it more quickly and reliably.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Telco CDNs also have a built-in cost advantage since traditional CDNs must lease bandwidth from them and build the operator's margin into their own cost model.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] In addition, by operating their own content delivery infrastructure, telco operators have better control over the utilization of their resources.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Content management operations performed by CDNs are usually applied without (or with very limited) information about the network (e.g., topology, utilization etc.) of the telco-operators with which they interact or have business relationships.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] These pose a number of challenges for the telco-operators who have a limited sphere of action in face of the impact of these operations on the utilization of their resources.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] In contrast, the deployment of telco-CDNs allows operators to implement their own content management operations, which enables them to have a better control over the utilization of their resources and, as such, provide better quality of service and experience to their end users.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] In June 2011, StreamingMedia.com reported that a group of TSPs had founded an Operator Carrier Exchange (OCX) to interconnect their networks and compete more directly against large traditional CDNs like Akamai and Limelight Networks, which have extensive PoPs worldwide.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] This way, telcos are building a Federated CDN offering, which is more interesting for a content provider willing to deliver its content to the aggregated audience of this federation.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] It is likely that in a near future, other telco CDN federations will be created.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] They will grow by enrollment of new telcos joining the federation and bringing network presence and their Internet subscriber bases to the existing ones.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] The Open Caching specification by Streaming Video Technology Alliance defines a set of APIs that allows a Content Provider to deliver its content using several CDNs in a consistent way, seeing each CDN provider the same way through these APIs.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Combining several CDN services allow Content Providers to not rely on a single CDN service, especially concerned to deal with high peak audience during live events.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] There are several ways to allocate traffic to a particular CDN among the list, either client-side CDN selection, or server-side (at the Content Provider's origin) or cloud-side (in the middle, between the content origin and the audience).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] CDN selection criteria can be performance, availability and cost.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Traditionally, CDNs have used the IP of the client's recursive DNS resolver to geo-locate the client.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] While this is a sound approach in many situations, this leads to poor client performance if the client uses a non-local recursive DNS resolver that is far away.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] For instance, a CDN may route requests from a client in India to its edge server in Singapore, if that client uses a public DNS resolver in Singapore, causing poor performance for that client.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Indeed, a recent study showed that in many countries where public DNS resolvers are in popular use, the median distance between the clients and their recursive DNS resolvers can be as high as a thousand miles.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] In August 2011, a global consortium of leading Internet service providers led by Google announced their official implementation of the edns-client-subnet IETF Internet Draft, which is intended to accurately localize DNS resolution responses.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] The initiative involves a limited number of leading DNS service providers, such as Google Public DNS, and CDN service providers as well.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] With the edns-client-subnet EDNS0 option, CDNs can now utilize the IP address of the requesting client's subnet when resolving DNS requests.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] This approach, called end-user mapping, has been adopted by CDNs and it has been shown to drastically reduce the round-trip latencies and improve performance for clients who use public DNS or other non-local resolvers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] However, the use of EDNS0 also has drawbacks as it decreases the effectiveness of caching resolutions at the recursive resolvers, increases the total DNS resolution traffic, and raises a privacy concern of exposing the client's subnet.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Virtualization technologies are being used to deploy virtual CDNs (vCDNs) (also known as a software-defined CDN or sd-CDN) with the goal to reduce content provider costs, and at the same time, increase elasticity and decrease service delay.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] With vCDNs, it is possible to avoid traditional CDN limitations, such as performance, reliability and availability since virtual caches are deployed dynamically (as virtual machines or containers) in physical servers distributed across the provider's geographical coverage.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] As the virtual cache placement is based on both the content type and server or end-user geographic location, the vCDNs have a significant impact on service delivery and network congestion.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] To boost performance, delivery to clients from servers can use alternate non-HTTP protocols such as WebRTC and WebSockets.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] In 2017, Addy Osmani of Google started referring to software solutions that could integrate naturally with the Responsive Web Design paradigm (with particular reference to the <picture> element) as **Image CDN**s.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] The expression referred to the ability of a web architecture to serve multiple versions of the same image through HTTP, depending on the properties of the browser requesting it, as determined by either the browser or the server-side logic.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] The purpose of Image CDNs was, in Google's vision, to serve high-quality images (or, better, images perceived as high-quality by the human eye) while preserving download speed, thus contributing to a great User experience (UX).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Arguably, the *Image CDN* term was originally a misnomer, as neither Cloudinary nor Imgix (the examples quoted by Google in the 2017 guide by Addy Osmani) were, at the time, a CDN in the classical sense of the term.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Shortly afterwards, though, several companies offered solutions that allowed developers to serve different versions of their graphical assets according to several strategies.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] Many of these solutions were built on top of traditional CDNs, such as Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly, Edgecast and Cloudflare.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/content-delivery-network] At the same time, other solutions that already provided an image multi-serving service joined the Image CDN definition by either offering CDN functionality natively (ImageEngine) or integrating with one of the existing CDNs (Cloudinary/Akamai, Imgix/Fastly).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Latency is physically a consequence of the limited velocity at which any physical interaction can propagate.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] The magnitude of this velocity is always less than or equal to the speed of light.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Therefore, every physical system with any physical separation (distance) between cause and effect will experience some sort of latency, regardless of the nature of the stimulation to which it has been exposed.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] The precise definition of latency depends on the system being observed or the nature of the simulation.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] In communications, the lower limit of latency is determined by the medium being used to transfer information.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] In reliable two-way communication systems, latency limits the maximum rate at which information can be transmitted, as there is often a limit on the amount of information that is in-flight at any given moment.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Perceptible latency has a strong effect on user satisfaction and usability in the field of human–machine interaction.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Online games are sensitive to latency (lag), since fast response times to new events occurring during a game session are rewarded while slow response times may carry penalties.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Due to a delay in transmission of game events, a player with a high-latency internet connection may show slow responses in spite of appropriate reaction time.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] This gives players with low-latency connections a technical advantage.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Trading using computers has developed to the point where millisecond improvements in network speeds offer a competitive advantage for financial institutions.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] However, in a non-trivial network, a typical packet will be forwarded over multiple links and gateways, each of which will not begin to forward the packet until it has been completely received.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] In such a network, the minimal latency is the sum of the transmission delay of each link, plus the forwarding latency of each gateway.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] In practice, minimal latency also includes queuing and processing delays.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Queuing delay occurs when a gateway receives multiple packets from different sources heading toward the same destination.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Since typically only one packet can be transmitted at a time, some of the packets must queue for transmission, incurring additional delay.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Processing delays are incurred while a gateway determines what to do with a newly received packet.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Bufferbloat can also cause increased latency that is an order of magnitude or more.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] The combination of propagation, serialization, queuing, and processing delays often produces a complex and variable network latency profile.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Latency limits total throughput in reliable two-way communication systems as described by the bandwidth-delay product.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Latency in optical fiber is largely a function of the speed of light.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] This would equate to a latency of 3.33 μs for every kilometer of path length.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] The index of refraction of most fiber optic cables is about 1.5, meaning that light travels about 1.5 times as fast in a vacuum as it does in the cable.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] This works out to about 5.0 μs of latency for every kilometer.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] In shorter metro networks, higher latency can be experienced due to extra distance in building risers and cross-connects.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] To calculate the latency of a connection, one has to know the distance traveled by the fiber, which is rarely a straight line, since it has to traverse geographic contours and obstacles, such as roads and railway tracks, as well as other rights-of-way.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Due to imperfections in the fiber, light degrades as it is transmitted through it.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] For distances of greater than 100 kilometers, amplifiers or regenerators are deployed.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Latency introduced by these components needs to be taken into account.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Low Earth orbit is sometimes used to cut this delay, at the expense of more complicated satellite tracking on the ground and requiring more satellites in the satellite constellation to ensure continuous coverage.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Audio latency is the delay between when an audio signal enters and when it emerges from a system.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Potential contributors to latency in an audio system include analog-to-digital conversion, buffering, digital signal processing, transmission time, digital-to-analog conversion and the speed of sound in air.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Video latency refers to the degree of delay between the time a transfer of a video stream is requested and the actual time that transfer begins.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Networks that exhibit relatively small delays are known as low-latency networks, while their counterparts are known as high-latency networks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Any individual workflow within a system of workflows can be subject to some type of operational latency.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] It may even be the case that an individual system may have more than one type of latency, depending on the type of participant or goal-seeking behavior.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] This is best illustrated by the following two examples involving air travel.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] From the point of view of a passenger, latency can be described as follows.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Suppose John Doe flies from London to New York.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] The latency of his trip is the time it takes him to go from his house in England to the hotel he is staying at in New York.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] This is independent of the throughput of the London-New York air link, whether there were 100 passengers a day making the trip or 10000, the latency of the trip would remain the same.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] From the point of view of flight operations personnel, latency can be entirely different.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Consider the staff at the London and New York airports.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Only a limited number of planes are able to make the transatlantic journey, so when one lands, they must prepare it for the return trip as quickly as possible.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] However, cleaning, refueling and loading the cargo can be done at the same time.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Passengers can only be loaded after cleaning is complete.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] The people involved in the turnaround are interested only in the time it takes for their individual tasks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] When all of the tasks are done at the same time, however, it is possible to reduce the latency to the length of the longest task.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] If some steps have prerequisites, it becomes more difficult to perform all steps in parallel.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] In the example above, the requirement to clean the plane before loading passengers results in a minimum latency longer than any single task.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Any mechanical process encounters limitations modeled by Newtonian physics.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] The behavior of disk drives provides an example of mechanical latency.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Here, it is the time seek time for the actuator arm to be positioned above the appropriate track and then rotational latency for the data encoded on a platter to rotate from its current position to a position under the disk read-and-write head.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Computers run instructions in the context of a process.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] In the context of computer multitasking, the execution of the process can be postponed if other processes are also executing.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] In addition, the operating system can schedule when to perform the action that the process is commanding.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] For example, suppose a process commands that a computer card's voltage output be set high-low-high-low and so on at a rate of 1000 Hz.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] The operating system schedules the process for each transition (high-low or low-high) based on a hardware clock, such as the High Precision Event Timer.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] The latency is the delay between the events generated by the hardware clock and the actual transitions of voltage from high to low or low to high.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Many desktop operating systems have performance limitations that create additional latency.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] The problem may be mitigated with real-time extensions and patches such as PREEMPT RT.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] On embedded systems, the real-time execution of instructions is often supported by a real-time operating system.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Note that in software systems, benchmarking against *average* and *median* latency can be misleading because a few outliers can distort them.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Instead, software architects and software developers should use "99th percentile".
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] In simulation applications, latency refers to the time delay, often measured in milliseconds, between initial input and output clearly discernible to the simulator trainee or simulator subject.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Latency is sometimes also called *transport delay*.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] Some authorities distinguish between latency and transport delay by using the term *latency* in the sense of the extra time delay of a system over and above the reaction time of the vehicle being simulated, but this requires detailed knowledge of the vehicle dynamics and can be controversial.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] In simulators with both visual and motion systems, it is particularly important that the latency of the motion system not be greater than of the visual system, or symptoms of simulator sickness may result.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] This is because, in the real world, motion cues are those of acceleration and are quickly transmitted to the brain, typically in less than 50 milliseconds; this is followed some milliseconds later by a perception of change in the visual scene.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] The visual scene change is essentially one of change of perspective or displacement of objects, such as the horizon, which takes some time to build up to discernible amounts after the initial acceleration that caused the displacement.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/latency-engineering] A simulator should, therefore, reflect the real-world situation by ensuring that the motion latency is equal to or less than that of the visual system and not the other way round.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] In computing, **load balancing** is the process of distributing a set of tasks over a set of resources (computing units) with the aim of making their overall processing more efficient.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can optimize response time and avoid unevenly overloading some compute nodes while other compute nodes are left idle.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is the subject of research in the field of parallel computers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Two main approaches exist: static algorithms, which do not take into account the state of the different machines, and dynamic algorithms, which are usually more general and more efficient but require exchanges of information between the different computing units, at the risk of a loss of efficiency.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] A load-balancing algorithm always tries to answer a specific problem.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Among other things, the nature of the tasks, the algorithmic complexity, the hardware architecture on which the algorithms will run as well as required error tolerance, must be taken into account.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Therefore compromise must be found to best meet application-specific requirements.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of load balancing algorithms critically depends on the nature of the tasks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the more information about the tasks is available at the time of decision making, the greater the potential for optimization.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Perfect knowledge of the execution time of each of the tasks allows to reach an optimal load distribution (see algorithm of prefix sum).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Unfortunately, this is in fact an idealized case.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Knowing the exact execution time of each task is an extremely rare situation.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] For this reason, there are several techniques to get an idea of the different execution times.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] First of all, when tasks are relatively homogeneous size, it is possible to consider that each of them will require approximately the average execution time.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the execution time is considerably irregular, other techniques may be used.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] One technique is to add some metadata to each task.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Depending on the previous execution time for similar metadata, it is possible to make inferences for a future task based on statistics.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] In some cases, tasks depend on each other.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] These interdependencies can be illustrated by a directed acyclic graph.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Intuitively, some tasks cannot begin until others are completed.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Assuming that the required time for each of the tasks is known in advance, an optimal execution order must lead to the minimization of the total execution time.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] However, this is an NP-hard problem and therefore can be difficult to solve exactly.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] There are algorithms, like job scheduler, that calculate optimal task distributions using metaheuristic methods.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Another feature of the tasks critical for the design of a load balancing algorithm is their ability to be broken down into subtasks during execution.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The *tree-shaped computation* algorithm presented later takes great advantage of this specificity.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm is "static" when it does not take into account the state of the system for the distribution of tasks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Thereby, the system state includes measures such as the load level (and sometimes even overload) of certain processors.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Instead, assumptions about the overall system are made beforehand, such as the arrival times and resource requirements of incoming tasks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] In addition, the number of processors, their respective power and communication speeds are known.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, static load balancing aims to associate a known set of tasks with the available processors in order to minimize a certain performance function.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The key design choice is the performance function.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing techniques are commonly centralized around a router, or master, which distributes the loads and optimizes the performance function.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This minimization can take into account information related to the tasks to be distributed, and derive an expected execution time.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The advantage of static algorithms is that they are easy to set up and can efficient in the case of fairly regular tasks (such as processing HTTP requests from a website).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] However, there is still some statistical variance in the assignment of tasks which can lead to the overloading of some computing units.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Unlike static load distribution algorithms, dynamic algorithms take into account the current load of each of the computing units (also called nodes) in the system.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] In this approach, tasks can be moved dynamically from an overloaded node to an underloaded node in order to receive faster processing.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] While these algorithms are much more complicated to design, they can improve performance, in particular, when the execution time varies greatly from one task to another.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing architecture can be more modular since it is not mandatory to have a specific node dedicated to the distribution of work.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] When tasks are uniquely assigned to a processor according to their state at a given moment, it is a unique assignment.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the tasks can be permanently redistributed according to the state of the system and its evolution, this is called dynamic assignment.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] A load balancing algorithm that requires too much communication in order to reach its decisions runs the risk of slowing down the resolution of the overall problem.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Parallel computing infrastructures are often composed of units of different computing power, which should be taken into account for the load distribution.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] For example, lower-powered units may receive requests that require a smaller amount of computation, or, in the case of homogeneous or unknown request sizes, receive fewer requests than larger units.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] For shared-memory computers, managing write conflicts greatly slows down the speed of individual execution of each computing unit.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] However, they can work perfectly well in parallel.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Conversely, in the case of message exchange, each of the processors can work at full speed.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, when it comes to collective message exchange, all processors are forced to wait for the slowest processors to start the communication phase.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] In reality, few systems fall into exactly one of the categories.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] In general, the processors each have an internal memory to store the data needed for the next calculations and are organized in successive clusters.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Often, these processing elements are then coordinated through distributed memory and message passing.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, the load balancing algorithm should be uniquely adapted to a parallel architecture.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Otherwise, there is a risk that the efficiency of parallel problem solving will be greatly reduced.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Adapting to the hardware structures seen above, there are two main categories of load balancing algorithms.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] On the one hand, the one where tasks are assigned by “master” and executed by “workers” who keep the master informed of the progress of their work, and the master can then take charge of assigning or reassigning the workload in case of the dynamic algorithm.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The literature refers to this as master-worker architecture.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] On the other hand, the control can be distributed between the different nodes.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The load balancing algorithm is then executed on each of them and the responsibility for assigning tasks (as well as re-assigning and splitting as appropriate) is shared.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The last category assumes a dynamic load balancing algorithm.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Since the design of each load balancing algorithm is unique, the previous distinction must be qualified.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Thus, it is also possible to have an intermediate strategy, with, for example, "master" nodes for each sub-cluster, which are themselves subject to a global "master".
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] There are also multi-level organizations, with an alternation between master-slave and distributed control strategies.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The latter strategies quickly become complex and are rarely encountered.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Designers prefer algorithms that are easier to control.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] In the context of algorithms that run over the very long term (servers, cloud...), the computer architecture evolves over time.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] However, it is preferable not to have to design a new algorithm each time.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] One parameter of a load balancing algorithm is therefore its ability to adapt to scalable hardware architecture.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This is called the scalability of the algorithm.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] An algorithm is called scalable for an input parameter when its performance remains relatively independent of the size of that parameter.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] When the algorithm is capable of adapting to a varying number of computing units, but the number of computing units must be fixed before execution, it is called moldable.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the algorithm is capable of dealing with a fluctuating amount of processors during its execution, the algorithm is said to be malleable.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancing algorithms are at least moldable.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Especially in large-scale computing clusters, it is not tolerable to execute a parallel algorithm that cannot withstand the failure of one single component.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, fault tolerant algorithms are being developed which can detect outages of processors and recover the computation.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] If the tasks are independent of each other, and if their respective execution time and the tasks can be subdivided, an optimal optimal algorithm is available under these assumptions.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] By dividing the tasks in such a way as to give the same amount of computation to each processor, all that remains to be done is to group the results together.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Using a prefix sum algorithm, this division can be calculated in logarithmic time with respect to the number of processors.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Most of the time, the execution time of a task is unknown and only rough approximations are available.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm may be efficient under these assumptions, but is less applicable when task durations are unknown.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Even if the execution time is not known in advance at all, static load distribution is always possible.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] In a round-robin algorithm, the first request is sent to the first server, then the next to the second, and so on down to the last.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Then it is started again, assigning the next request to the first server, and so on.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This algorithm can be weighted such that the most powerful units receive the largest number of requests and receive them first.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Randomized static load balancing is simply a matter of randomly assigning tasks to the different servers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] If, on the other hand, the number of tasks is known in advance, it is even more efficient to calculate a random permutation in advance.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This avoids communication costs for each assignment.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] There is no longer a need for a distribution master because every processor knows what task is assigned to it.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Even if the number of tasks is unknown, it is still possible to avoid communication with a pseudo-random assignment generation known to all processors.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The performance of this strategy (measured in total execution time for a given fixed set of tasks) decreases with the maximum size of the tasks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Master-worker schemes are among the simplest dynamic load balancing algorithms.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] A master distributes the workload to all workers (also sometimes referred to as "slaves").
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Initially, all workers are idle and report this to the master.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The master answers worker requests and distributes the tasks to them.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] When he has no more tasks to give, he informs the workers so that they stop asking for tasks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This scheme can distribute work evenly when assignment overhead is low.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Without taking into account the time needed for the assignment, the execution time would be comparable to the prefix sum seen above.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The problem with this algorithm is that it has difficulty adapting to a large number of processors because of the high amount of necessary communications.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This lack of scalability makes it quickly inoperable in very large servers or very large parallel computers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] However, the quality of the algorithm can be greatly improved by replacing the master with a task list that can be used by different processors.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Although this algorithm can be said to be slightly more difficult to implement, it can improve scalability, although still insufficient for very large computing centers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Another technique to overcome scalability problems when the time needed for task completion is unknown is work stealing.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The approach consists of assigning to each processor a certain number of tasks in a random or predefined manner, then allowing inactive processors to "steal" work from active or overloaded processors.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Several implementations of this concept exist, defined by a task division model and by the rules determining the exchange between processors.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] While this technique can be particularly effective, it is difficult to implement because it is necessary to ensure that communication does not become the primary occupation of the processors instead of solving the problem.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] In the case of atomic tasks, two main strategies can be distinguished, those where the processors with low load offer their computing capacity to those with the highest load, and those were the most loaded units wish to lighten the workload assigned to them.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] It has been shown that when the network is heavily loaded, it is more efficient for the least loaded units to offer their availability and when the network is lightly loaded, it is the overloaded processors that require support from the most inactive ones.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This rule of thumb limits the number of exchanged messages.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] In the case where one starts from a single large task that cannot be divided beyond an atomic level, a "Tree-Shaped computation" algorithm can be used, where the parent task is distributed in a work tree.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Initially, many processors have an empty task, except one that works sequentially on it.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Idle processors issue requests randomly to other processors (not necessarily active).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] If the latter is able to subdivide the task it is working on, it does so by sending part of its work to the node making the request.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] It is then necessary to send a termination signal to the parent processor when the subtask is completed so that it, in turn, sends the message to its parent until it reaches the root of the tree.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] When the first processor, i.e. the root, has finished, a global termination message can be broadcast.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] In the end, it is necessary to assemble the results by going back up the tree.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The efficiency of such an algorithm is close to the prefix sum when the job cutting and communication time is not too high compared to the work to be done.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] To avoid too high communication costs, it is possible to imagine a list of jobs on shared memory.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Therefore, a request is simply reading from a certain position on this shared memory at the request of the master processor.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] In addition to efficient problem solving through parallel computations, load balancing algorithms are widely used in HTTP request management where a site with a large audience must be able to handle a large number of requests per second.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] One of the most commonly used applications of load balancing is to provide a single Internet service from multiple servers, sometimes known as a server farm.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Commonly load-balanced systems include popular web sites, large Internet Relay Chat networks, high-bandwidth File Transfer Protocol (FTP) sites, Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) servers, Domain Name System (DNS) servers, and databases.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Round-robin DNS is an alternate method of load balancing that does not require a dedicated software or hardware node.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] In this technique, multiple IP addresses are associated with a single domain name; clients are given IP in a round-robin fashion.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] IP is assigned to clients with a short expiration so the client is more likely to use a different IP the next time they access the Internet service being requested.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Another more effective technique for load-balancing using DNS is to delegate www.example.org as a sub-domain whose zone is served by each of the same servers that are serving the website.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This technique works particularly well where individual servers are spread geographically on the Internet.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] However, the zone file for www.example.org on each server is different such that each server resolves its own IP Address as the A-record.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This way, when a server is down, its DNS will not respond and the web service does not receive any traffic.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] If the line to one server is congested, the unreliability of DNS ensures less HTTP traffic reaches that server.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Furthermore, the quickest DNS response to the resolver is nearly always the one from the network's closest server, ensuring geo-sensitive load-balancing .
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] A short TTL on the A-record helps to ensure traffic is quickly diverted when a server goes down.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Consideration must be given to the possibility that this technique may cause individual clients to switch between individual servers in mid-session.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Another approach to load balancing is to deliver a list of server IPs to the client, and then to have the client randomly select the IP from the list on each connection.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This essentially relies on all clients generating similar loads, and the law of large numbers to achieve a reasonably flat load distribution across servers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] With this approach, the method of delivery of a list of IPs to the client can vary and may be implemented as a DNS list (delivered to all the clients without any round-robin), or via hardcoding it to the list.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] If a "smart client" is used, detecting that a randomly selected server is down and connecting randomly again, it also provides fault tolerance.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] For Internet services, a server-side load balancer is usually a software program that is listening on the port where external clients connect to access services.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer forwards requests to one of the "backend" servers, which usually replies to the load balancer.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This allows the load balancer to reply to the client without the client ever knowing about the internal separation of functions.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] It also prevents clients from contacting back-end servers directly, which may have security benefits by hiding the structure of the internal network and preventing attacks on the kernel's network stack or unrelated services running on other ports.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancers provide a mechanism for doing something special in the event that all backend servers are unavailable.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This might include forwarding to a backup load balancer or displaying a message regarding the outage.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] It is also important that the load balancer itself does not become a single point of failure.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Usually, load balancers are implemented in high-availability pairs which may also replicate session persistence data if required by the specific application.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Certain applications are programmed with immunity to this problem, by offsetting the load balancing point over differential sharing platforms beyond the defined network.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The sequential algorithms paired to these functions are defined by flexible parameters unique to the specific database.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Numerous scheduling algorithms, also called load-balancing methods, are used by load balancers to determine which back-end server to send a request to.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Simple algorithms include random choice, round robin, or least connections.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] An important issue when operating a load-balanced service is how to handle information that must be kept across the multiple requests in a user's session.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] If this information is stored locally on one backend server, then subsequent requests going to different backend servers would not be able to find it.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This might be cached information that can be recomputed, in which case load-balancing a request to a different backend server just introduces a performance issue.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Ideally, the cluster of servers behind the load balancer should not be session-aware, so that if a client connects to any backend server at any time the user experience is unaffected.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This is usually achieved with a shared database or an in-memory session database like Memcached.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] One basic solution to the session data issue is to send all requests in a user session consistently to the same backend server.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This is known as "persistence" or "stickiness".
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] A significant downside to this technique is its lack of automatic failover: if a backend server goes down, its per-session information becomes inaccessible, and any sessions depending on it are lost.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The same problem is usually relevant to central database servers; even if web servers are "stateless" and not "sticky", the central database is (see below).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Assignment to a particular server might be based on a username, client IP address, or random.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Because of changes in the client's perceived address resulting from DHCP, network address translation, and web proxies this method may be unreliable.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Random assignments must be remembered by the load balancer, which creates a burden on storage.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] If the load balancer is replaced or fails, this information may be lost, and assignments may need to be deleted after a timeout period or during periods of high load to avoid exceeding the space available for the assignment table.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The random assignment method also requires that clients maintain some state, which can be a problem, for example when a web browser has disabled the storage of cookies.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Sophisticated load balancers use multiple persistence techniques to avoid some of the shortcomings of any one method.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Another solution is to keep the per-session data in a database.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This can reduce performance because it increases the load on the database: the database is best used to store information less transient than per-session data.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] To prevent a database from becoming a single point of failure, and to improve scalability, the database is often replicated across multiple machines, and load balancing is used to spread the query load across those replicas.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Microsoft's ASP.net State Server technology is an example of a session database.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] All servers in a web farm store their session data on State Server and any server in the farm can retrieve the data.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] When the client is a web browser, one approach is to store the per-session data in the browser itself.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] One way to achieve this is to use a browser cookie, suitably time-stamped and encrypted.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Storing session data on the client is generally the preferred solution: then the load balancer is free to pick any backend server to handle a request.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] However, this method of state-data handling may be unsuitable for some complex business logic scenarios, where the session state payload is large and recomputing it with every request on a server is not feasible.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] URL rewriting has major security issues because the end-user can easily alter the submitted URL and thus change session streams.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Yet another solution to storing persistent data is to associate a name with each block of data, and use a distributed hash table to pseudo-randomly assign that name to one of the available servers, and then store that block of data in the assigned server.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Hardware and software load balancers may have a variety of special features.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The fundamental feature of a load balancer is to be able to distribute incoming requests over a number of backend servers in the cluster according to a scheduling algorithm.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] A ratio can be manually assigned to cause some backend servers to get a greater share of the workload than others.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This is sometimes used as a simple way to account for some servers having more capacity than others, though it may not always work as desired.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] When the number of available servers drops below a certain number, or the load gets too high, standby servers can be brought online.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] request can become a major part of the demand on the Web Server's CPU; as the demand increases, users will see slower response times, as the TLS overhead is distributed among Web servers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] To remove this demand on Web servers, a balancer can terminate TLS connections, passing HTTPS requests as HTTP requests to the Web servers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] If the balancer itself is not overloaded, this does not noticeably degrade the performance perceived by end-users.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The downside of this approach is that all of the TLS processing is concentrated on a single device (the balancer) which can become a new bottleneck.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Some load balancer appliances include specialized hardware to process TLS.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Instead of upgrading the load balancer, which is quite expensive dedicated hardware, it may be cheaper to forgo TLS offload and add a few web servers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Also, some server vendors such as Oracle/Sun now incorporate cryptographic acceleration hardware into their CPUs such as the T2000.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] F5 Networks incorporates a dedicated TLS acceleration hardware card in their local traffic manager (LTM) which is used for encrypting and decrypting TLS traffic.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] One clear benefit to TLS offloading in the balancer is that it enables it to do balancing or content switching based on data in the HTTPS request.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] attacks and generally offload work from the servers to a more efficient platform.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] compression available in all modern web browsers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The larger the response and the further away the client is, the more this feature can improve response times.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The trade-off is that this feature puts additional CPU demand on the load balancer and could be done by web servers instead.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Different vendors use different terms for this, but the idea is that normally each HTTP request from each client is a different TCP connection.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This feature utilises HTTP/1.1 to consolidate multiple HTTP requests from multiple clients into a single TCP socket to the back-end servers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The load balancer can buffer responses from the server and spoon-feed the data out to slow clients, allowing the webserver to free a thread for other tasks faster than it would if it had to send the entire request to the client directly.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] An option for asymmetrical load distribution, where request and reply have different network paths.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The balancer polls servers for application layer health and removes failed servers from the pool.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The balancer stores static content so that some requests can be handled without contacting the servers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can arbitrarily modify traffic on the way through.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Some balancers can hide HTTP error pages, remove server identification headers from HTTP responses, and encrypt cookies so that end users cannot manipulate them.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] , the ability to give different priorities to different traffic.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Most load balancers can send requests to different servers based on the URL being requested, assuming the request is not encrypted (HTTP) or if it is encrypted (via HTTPS) that the HTTPS request is terminated (decrypted) at the load balancer.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Authenticate users against a variety of authentication sources before allowing them access to a website.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] At least one balancer allows the use of a scripting language to allow custom balancing methods, arbitrary traffic manipulations, and more.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Firewalls can prevent direct connections to backend servers, for network security reasons.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Intrusion prevention systems offer application layer security in addition to the network/transport layer offered by firewall security.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing can be useful in applications with redundant communications links.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] For example, a company may have multiple Internet connections ensuring network access if one of the connections fails.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] A failover arrangement would mean that one link is designated for normal use, while the second link is used only if the primary link fails.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Using load balancing, both links can be in use all the time.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] A device or program monitors the availability of all links and selects the path for sending packets.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The use of multiple links simultaneously increases the available bandwidth.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) facilitates an Ethernet to have an arbitrary topology, and enables per flow pair-wise load splitting by way of Dijkstra's algorithm, without configuration and user intervention.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, whom in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The IEEE approved the IEEE 802.1aq standard in May 2012, also known as Shortest Path Bridging (SPB).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] SPB allows all links to be active through multiple equal-cost paths, provides faster convergence times to reduce downtime, and simplifies the use of load balancing in mesh network topologies (partially connected and/or fully connected) by allowing traffic to load share across all paths of a network.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] SPB is designed to reduce configuration errors and preserves the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at Layer 2.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Many telecommunications companies have multiple routes through their networks or to external networks.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] They use sophisticated load balancing to shift traffic from one path to another to avoid network congestion on any particular link, and sometimes to minimize the cost of transit across external networks or improve network reliability.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Another way of using load balancing is in network monitoring activities.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Load balancers can be used to split huge data flows into several sub-flows and use several network analyzers, each reading a part of the original data.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This can be used for monitoring fast networks like 10GbE or STM64, where complex processing of the data may not be possible at wire speed.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is widely used in data center networks to distribute traffic across many existing paths between any two servers.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] It allows more efficient use of network bandwidth and reduces provisioning costs.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] In general, load balancing in datacenter networks can be classified as either static or dynamic.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Static load balancing distributes traffic by computing a hash of the source and destination addresses and port numbers of traffic flows and using it to determine how flows are assigned to one of the existing paths.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic load balancing assigns traffic flows to paths by monitoring bandwidth use on different paths.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Dynamic assignments can also be proactive or reactive.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] In the former case, the assignment is fixed once made, while in the latter the network logic keeps monitoring available paths and shifts flows across them as network utilization changes (with arrival of new flows or completion of existing ones).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] A comprehensive overview of load balancing in datacenter networks has been made available.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Load balancing is often used to implement failover—the continuation of service after the failure of one or more of its components.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] The components are monitored continually (e.g., web servers may be monitored by fetching known pages), and when one becomes unresponsive, the load balancer is informed and no longer sends traffic to it.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] When a component comes back online, the load balancer starts rerouting traffic to it.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] For this to work, there must be at least one component in excess of the service's capacity (N+1 redundancy).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This can be much less expensive and more flexible than failover approaches where every single live component is paired with a single backup component that takes over in the event of a failure (dual modular redundancy).
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Some RAID systems can also utilize hot spare for a similar effect.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] This technique can increase fault tolerance by enabling quick substitutions for the most complicated, most failure-prone parts of a system.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] However, it can make the load balancer itself a single point of failure.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] To maintain the necessary high throughput and low latency, organizations commonly deploy load balancing tools capable of advanced TCP optimizations, connection pooling, and adaptive scheduling.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] Such features help distribute incoming data requests evenly across servers or nodes, prevent congestion, and ensure that compute resources remain efficiently utilized.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] When deployed in large-scale or high-performance AI environments, load balancers also mitigate bandwidth constraints and accommodate varying data governance requirements—particularly when sensitive training data cannot be sent to third-party cloud services.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] By routing data locally (on-premises) or across private clouds, load balancers allow AI workflows to avoid public-cloud bandwidth limits, reduce transit costs, and maintain compliance with regulatory standards.
[src:aws-global-accelerator/load-balancing-computing] As AI models expand in size (often measured by billions or even trillions of parameters), load balancing for data ingestion has grown in importance for maintaining the reliability, scalability, and cost efficiency of AI factories.
